  "application": "The father made a promise conditioned on the son marrying the politician daughter within eighteen months, and the son performed by marrying within fourteen months. That performance supplies consideration in substance, even if the son already intended to propose. Nonetheless, the bargain is explicitly conditioned on marriage, so it is an agreement upon consideration of marriage and ordinarily must be in a signed writing to be enforceable. There was no signed writing. The father also promised to assume responsibility for an existing debt of the son, which is another category that ordinarily requires a signed writing. Although the father was primarily motivated by an anticipated tax deduction, that motivation was a hoped for consequence rather than a bargained for benefit flowing from the son to the father. The son did not promise to confer a direct economic benefit on the father; the marriage was the requested performance. Because the father expected benefit depends on tax law rather than on the son performance creating a direct pecuniary advantage to the father, the primary purpose exception is unlikely to remove the promise from the writing requirement. The father later discovery that no tax deduction was available is a unilateral mistake about his own motive and does not supply a basis to enforce the promise without the required writing; if anything, it would be asserted as a defense, not as a substitute for the writing requirement.",
  "conclusion": "No. The father oral promise is not enforceable because it is an agreement made upon consideration of marriage and also a promise to pay the debt of another, both of which generally require a signed writing, and the primary purpose exception is unlikely to apply on these facts."
}

